l Resolution\n|| 2005\n|-\n|| Iraqi Surge\n|| 2007\n|-\n||Iraqi Sovereignty\n|| 2009\n|-\n|| New Dawn\n|| 2010\n|-\n|| [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] <br> [[File:Streamer AFGCS.PNG|150px]]\n|| Transition I\n|| 2011\u20132012\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Unit decorations ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! Ribbon\n! Award\n! Year\n! Notes\n|-\n||[[File:Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|50px]]\n||[[Meritorious Unit Commendation]] (Army)\n|| 1968\n|| VIETNAM \n|-\n||[[File:Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|50px]]\n||[[Meritorious Unit Commendation]] (Army)\n||\n|| SOUTHWEST ASIA\n|-\n||[[File:Army Superior Unit Award ribbon.svg|50px]]\n||[[Army Superior Unit Award]] (Army)\n|| 1997\n|| \n|-\n||[[File:Croix de Guerre 1939-1945 ribbon.svg|50px]]\n||[[Croix de guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|French Croix de Guerre]], with Palm\n||\n|| KASSERINE\n|-\n||[[File:Croix de Guerre 1939-1945 ribbon.svg|50px]]\n||[[Croix de guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|French Croix de Guerre]], with Palm\n||\n|| NORMANDY\n|-\n|| [[File:Fourrag\u00e8re CG.png|30px]]\n|| French Croix de guerre, <br>World War II, Fourragere ||\n|| \n|-\n|| [[File:BelgianFourragere.png|50px]]\n|| [[Belgian Fourragere]] || 1940 ||\n|-\n|| || Cited in the [[Order of the Day]] of the Belgian Army|| || For action at MONS\n|-\n|| || Cited in the Order of the Day of the Belgian Army || ||For action at EUPEN-MALMEDY\n|-\n||[[File:Gallantry Cross Unit Citation.png|50px]]\n||[[Republic of Vietnam Cross of Gallantry]], with Palm\n||1965\u20131968\n||For service in [[Vietnam]]\n|-\n||[[File:Vietnam Civil Actions Unit Citation.png|50px]]\n||[[Republic of Vietnam Civil Action Honor Medal|Republic of Vietnam Civil Action Unit Citation]]\n||1965\u20131970\n||For service in [[Vietnam]]\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Big Red One]]'' (1980), a movie about the division's experiences in World War II written by [[Samuel Fuller]] who served in the division during World War II.\n* [[Cantigny]], the former estate of Col. Robert R. McCormick, is where the 1st Infantry Division Museum is located. The museum showcases the history of the 1st Infantry Division, from their involvement in World War I to the present, along with several tanks situated outside the museum dating from World War I to the present.<ref>\nHannah Marsh, \"Memory in World War I American museum exhibits\" (MA thesis, Kansas State University, 2015, [http://krex.k-state.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/2097/18813/HannahMarsh2015.pdf?sequence=5 online])</ref>\n* [[Iraq Assistance Group]], a former joint command coordinating the coalition [[military transition team]] mission in Iraq which was formed from the 1st Infantry Division.\n* ''[[Call of Duty 2: Big Red One]]'', an expansion for the first-person shooter video game ''[[Call of Duty 2]]'' with a focus on the division's operations in World War II.\n* ''[[Call of Duty: WWII]]'' has players take on the role of Ronald \"Red\" Daniels, a private and part of \"The Bloody First\", following the operations of the division from the D-Day landings, up to the capture of the Rhineland.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist |group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{ACMH|url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/lineages/branches/div/001id.htm| article = 1st Infantry Division Honors}}\n{{reflist}}\n<ref>Office of the Theater Historian 1948, ''Order of Battle of the United States Army World War II Divisions 1945'', Paris.</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Felix G. \"Third Graders at War\" The true story of a Cavalry Scout during Operation Desert Storm {{ISBN|978-1-4575-0152-4}}\n* Rohan, John ''Rags, the Dog Who Went to War'', Diggory Press, {{ISBN|978-1-84685-364-7}}\n* Gantter, Raymond ''Roll Me Over, An Infantryman's World War II'', Ivy Books, {{ISBN|0-8041-1605-9}}\n* Stanton, Shelby, ''Vietnam Order of Battle: A Complete Illustrated Reference to the U.S. Army and Allied Ground Forces in Vietnam, 1961\u20131973'', Stackpole Books 2006 {{ISBN|0-8117-0071-2}}\n* Wheeler, James Scott. ''The Big Red One: America's Legendary 1st Infantry Division from World War I to Desert Storm'' (2nd ed. University Press of Kansas, 2007), the standard history; 710pp\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|1st Infantry Division (United States)}}\n* [http://www.1id.army.mil/ Official 1st Infantry Division website]\n* [http://www.1stid.org Society of the First Infantry Division]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722180523/http://www.1id.army.mil/bigredone/magazines/ Duty First: The 1st Infantry Division's award-winning quarterly magazine]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130602011224/http://firstdivisionmuseum.org/ First Division Museum at Cantigny Park]\n* [http://www.lonesentry.com/gi_stories_booklets/1stinfantry/ The First! The Story of the 1st Infantry Division (World War II divisional history booklet, 1945)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080117010522/http://www.bsu.edu/wipb/echoesofwar/index.asp ''Echoes of War: Stories from the Big Red One'' Interactive PBS documentary about the 1st Infantry Div.]\n* [http://www.1stInfantryDivision.de 1st Infantry Division Living History Group \u2013 Germany]\n* [http://dmr.bsu.edu/cdm4/collection.php?CISOROOT=/CtgnyOrHis Cantigny First Division Oral Histories], includes freely accessible video oral history interviews with veterans of the U.S. Army's First Infantry Division\n\n; Media\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.archives.arc.2569480|name=Big Picture: The Big Red One}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.ntis.ava10749vnb1|name=\"The Fighting First (1946)\"}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.dod.dimoc.27007|name=STAFF FILM REPORT 66-5A (1966)}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.dod.dimoc.26958|name=STAFF FILM REPORT 66-1OA (1966)}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.dod.dimoc.26966|name=STAFF FILM REPORT 66-17A (1966)}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.dod.dimoc.26972|name=STAFF FILM REPORT 66-21A (1966)}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.dod.dimoc.26973|nam