ted musical films]]\n[[Category:Frozen (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chris Buck]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Peter Del Vecho]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Christophe Beck]]\n[[Category:Films set in Scandinavia]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Animation Studios films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n", "name_user": "AverageLogic", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frozen_II"}
{"title_page": "Paola Rojas", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Paola Rojas\n| image         = Paola Rojas.jpg\n| imagesize     = 220px\n| caption       = \n| birth_name     = Paola Rojas Hinojosa\n| birth_date     =  {{birth date and age|1976|11|20}} \n| birth_place      = [[Mexico City]], [[Distrito Federal]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| yearsactive   = \n| spouse        = Zague (2009 - 2018 Div.) \n| website      = \n| notable role  = \n}}\n'''Paola Rojas''' (born '''Paola Rojas Hinojosa'''; November 20, 1976) is a Mexican television [[news anchor]]. Born in [[Mexico City]], [[Distrito Federal]], [[Mexico]], Rojas's education was started in the [[fine arts]] at a very young age by her father Jorge Rojas.\n\n== Biography ==\nRojas career started at the radio station [[Vox FM]], where she worked aside the famous Mexican journalist [[Ricardo Rocha (Mexican footbsller)|Ricardo Rocha]] in the ''[[Detr\u00e1s de la Noticia]]'' program.\n\nNot long after that, she moved to the Music Network [[Telehit]], where she worked with [[Horacio Villalobos]] in ''[[V\u00e1lvula de Escape]]''.\n\nIn 2002, she also participated as a judge in the reality show [[Popstars (TV show)|Popstars]] and then she got her own program called ''[[Encuentros Cercanos]]'' besides her good friend [[Poncho Vera]].\n\nDuring that time she hosted another radio show called ''[[La Talacha]]'' in [[XEW-AM|W Radio]], along with [[Ricardo Zamora]], [[Fernanda Tapia]] and [[Mariana del Valle]]. She also formed part of the team of ''[[Planeta 3]]'', with [[Eduardo Videgaray]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n San Crist\u00f3bal]].\n\nThen she moved the news program ''[[El Cristal con que se mira]]'', and months later she became part of [[Televisa]]'s news team as the host of ''[[A las Tres]]'' which she still hosts until today. She also host a weekly radio news program airing on the Radio Formula network.\n\nCurrently, Paola received an award for being one of Televisa's most successful women, called ''Mujer Activa''. She was married to [[Mexican people|Mexican]] soccer legend, [[Luis Roberto Alves]], Zague.\n\nShe is currently represented by [http://www.shineentertainmentmedia.com/paola-rojas Shine Entertainment Media].\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=2021818|name=Paola Rojas}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080817104500/http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/artistas/383656.html Biography at Esmas.com] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rojas, Paola}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Mexican television personalities]]\n[[Category:Mexican women journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Paola Rojas\n| image         = Paola Rojas.jpg\n| imagesize     = 220px\n| caption       = \n| birth_name     = Paola Rojas Hinojosa\n| birth_date     =  {{birth date and age|1976|11|20}} \n| birth_place      = [[Mexico City]], [[Distrito Federal]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| yearsactive   = \n| spouse        = Zague (2009 - 2018 Div.) \n| website      = \n| notable role  = \n}}\n'''Paola Rojas''' (born '''Paola Rojas Hinojosa'''; November 20, 1976) is a Mexican television [[news anchor]]. Born in [[Mexico City]], [[Distrito Federal]], [[Mexico]], Rojas's education was started in the [[fine arts]] at a very young age by her father Jorge Rojas.\n\n== Biography ==\nRojas career started at the radio station [[Vox FM]], where she worked aside the famous Mexican journalist [[Ricardo Rocha (Mexican footbsller)|Ricardo Rocha]] in the ''[[Detr\u00e1s de la Noticia]]'' program.\n\nNot long after that, she moved to the Music Network [[Telehit]], where she worked with [[Horacio Villalobos]] in ''[[V\u00e1lvula de Escape]]''.\n\nIn 2002, she also participated as a judge in the reality show [[Popstars (TV show)|Popstars]] and then she got her own program called ''[[Encuentros Cercanos]]'' besides her good friend [[Poncho Vera]].\n\nDuring that time she hosted another radio show called ''[[La Talacha]]'' in [[XEW-AM|W Radio]], along with [[Ricardo Zamora]], [[Fernanda Tapia]] and [[Mariana del Valle]]. She also formed part of the team of ''[[Planeta 3]]'', with [[Eduardo Videgaray]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n San Crist\u00f3bal]].\n\nThen she moved the news program ''[[El Cristal con que se mira]]'', and months later she became part of [[Televisa]]'s news team as the host of ''[[A las Tres]]'' which she still hosts until today. She also host a weekly radio news program airing on the Radio Formula network.\n\nCurrently, Paola received an award for being one of Televisa's most successful women, called ''Mujer Activa''. She was married to [[Mexican people|Mexican]] soccer legend, [[Luis Roberto Alves]], Zague.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=2021818|name=Paola Rojas}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080817104500/http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/artistas/383656.html Biography at Esmas.com] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rojas, Paola}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Mexican television personalities]]\n[[Category:Mexican women journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Gvldz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Website added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paola_Rojas"}
{"title_page": "Prostitution in Trinidad and Tobago", "text_new": "'''Prostitution in Trinidad and Tobago''' is legal but related activities such as brothel keeping, soliciting and pimping are illegal.<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=3 January 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"soa86\">{{cite web|url=http://rgd.legalaffairs.gov.tt/laws2/alphabetical_list/lawspdfs/11.28.pdf |title=Laws of Trinidad and Tobago : Sexual Offences Act : Chapter 11:28 : Act 27 of 1986 |date=31 December 2015 |website=Rgd.legalaffairs.gov.tt |accessdate=2017-01-11}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Trinidad]], [[Port of Spain]] is the main place of sex work,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caribbean360.com/news/trinidad_tobago_news/women-trafficked-for-prostitution-and-forced-marriage-in-trinidad|title=Women trafficked for prostitution and forced marriage in Trinidad - Caribbean360|date=24 January 2014|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ips\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/1996/02/trinidad-and-tobago-child-prostitution-is-a-thriving-business/|title=Trinidad and Tobago: Child Prostitution Is A Thriving Business - Inter Press Service|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> including [[street prostitution]] on Roberts and Murray Streets.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=John|title=What about street prostitutes, Louis?|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/letters/2011/02/14/what-about-street-prostitutes-louis|website=The Trinidad Guardian Newspaper|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=15 February 2011}}</ref> New [[brothels]] continue to open across the country, particularly in the south where they are incorporated into small bars and rum shops and are difficult to detect, and in central, where they operate out of a normal-looking flats in a neighbourhood.<ref name=\"state16\" /> Many of the sex workers come from [[Colombia]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Cuba]]. Some regularly commute between their home nation and Trinidad.<ref name=\"pope\">{{cite book|last1=Pope|first1=Cynthia|last2=White|first2=Ren\u00e9e T.|last3=Malow|first3=Robert|title=HIV/AIDS : global frontiers in prevention/intervention|date=2009|publisher=Routledge|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0415953832}}</ref>\n\nProstitution in less common in [[Tobago]], some prostitutes from Trinidad move to Tobago for the tourist season.<ref name=\"guard\" /><ref name=\"ipsnews\" />\n\nThe country is a [[sex tourism]] destination.<ref name=\"campbell\">{{cite book|last1=Niblett|first1=Michael|last2=Campbell|first2=Chris |title=The Caribbean: Aesthetics, World-Ecology, Politics (Postcolonialism Across the Disciplines)|date=31 May 2016|publisher=Liverpool University Press|isbn=978-1781382950}}</ref> \nTobago is also known as a destination for [[female sex tourism]].<ref name=\"guard\">{{cite web|last1=Fido|first1=Austin|title=The shady side of paradise|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2015-09-20/shady-side-paradise|website=Trinidad & Tobago Guardian|accessdate=23 December 2017|date=20 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Sex trafficking]] is a problem in the country,<ref name=\"sextour\">{{cite web|title=16 Caribbean Nations Where Sex Trafficking Remains A Problem {{!}} News Americas Now:Caribbean and Latin America Daily News|url=http://www.newsamericasnow.com/16-caribbean-nations-where-sex-trafficking-remains-a-problem/|website=News Americas Now|accessdate=30 December 2017|date=30 June 2016}}</ref> as is [[child prostitution]].<ref name=\"ips\" />\n\n==Legislation==\nBeing a former [[British Empire|British colony]], much of the prostitution law mirrors that of the [[UK]]:\n\n* The 1921 Summary Offences Act<ref name=\"sum21\">{{cite web|title=Laws of Trinidad and Tobago: Summary Offences Act Chapter 11:02|url=http://rgd.legalaffairs.gov.tt/laws2/alphabetical_list/lawspdfs/11.02.pdf|publisher=Government of Trinidad and Tobago|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=1921}}</ref> \n** Section 46: any woman loitering about and soliciting passers-by for the purpose of prostitution, on the second occasion, may be deemed a rogue and vagabond, and shall be liable to imprisonment for two months\n* The 1986 Sexual Offences Act<ref name=\"soa86\" />\n**Section 17: Any person who procures another for prostitution; or procures another to become an inmate of or to frequent a brothel; is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for fifteen years\n** Section 19: A person who detains another against that other's will in any brothel, is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for ten years.\n** Section 22: A person who keeps or manages or acts or assists in the management of a brothel; or being the tenant, lessee, occupier or person in charge of any premises, knowingly permits the premises or any part thereof to be used as a brothel or for the purposes of prostitution; is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for five years.\n** Section 23. (1) A person who\u2014\n***(a) knowingly lives wholly or in part on the earnings of prostitution; or\n***(b) in any place solicits for immoral purposes,\n::is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for five years\n* Human trafficking is dealt with by the Trafficking In Persons Act 2011.<ref name=\"newsday1\">{{cite web|last1=Connelly|first1=Corey|title=100 Arrivals Weekly|url=http://archives.newsday.co.tt/2015/07/12/100-arrivals-weekly/|website=Trinidad and Tobago Newsday|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=12 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Colonial period===\nDuring the slave period, slaves could sometimes be hired as prostitutes.<ref name=\"plant\">{{cite book|last1=Trotman|first1=David Vincent|title=Crime in Trinidad : conflict and control in a plantation society, 1838-1900|url=https://archive.org/details/crimeintrinidadc0000trot|url-access=registration|date=1986|publisher=University of Tennessee Press|location=Knoxville, TN|isbn=978-0870494918|edition=1st}}</ref> After the abolition of slavery (1838), many [[mulatto]] women became prostitutes or brothel madams, often moving from rural areas to towns such as Port of Spain.<ref name=\"plant\" />\n\nIn an effort to control the spread of [[sexually transmitted infections|STIs]] the Contagious Diseases Ordinance was introduced in 1869.<ref name=\"plant\" /> This was based in the similar [[Contagious Diseases Acts|British Act of 1864]]. Prostitutes were required to be registered and have regular examinations for STIs.<ref name=\"plant\" /> The ordinance was suspended in 1872 and reintroduced in 1875.<ref name=\"plant\" /> The register showed a significant number of prostitutes to be working in Port of Spain and [[San Fernando, Trinidad and Tobago|San Fernando]].<ref name=\"colonial\" /> Unscrupulous policemen took advantage of the ordinance to demand sexual favours. In  Port of Spain, a Sergeant Holder was given unlimited power to enforce the ordinance. He abused his position and, following an investigation brought about by a complaint, was dismissed from the force.<ref name=\"plant\" /> The ordinance was abolished in 1887.<ref name=\"plant\" />\n\nThe sugar slump of the 1880s<ref name=\"colonial\" /> brought many more women to the towns, turning to prostitution to try and make a living.<ref name=\"plant\" /> At this time, Port of Spain was reported to have more prostitutes than any other town in the [[West Indies]].<ref name=\"colonial\">{{cite book|last1=Brereton|first1=Bridget|title=Race relations in colonial Trinidad, 1870-1900|date=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0521523134|edition=Paperback}}</ref> Most of the taverns in the town were brothels, and the best brothel was reputed to be the \"British Coffee House\", run by a Mrs Peery.<ref name=\"plant\" /> Many of the prostitutes were underage and lived on the streets.<ref name=\"colonial\" />\n\n===1930's===\nDuring the [[Great Depression]] in the 1930s, more women turned to prostitution. In his book, ''Calypso and Society'', [[Gordon Rohlehr]] noted: \"Some singers, indeed, presented the vocation of prostitution as the only alternative to that of housewifery, and warned young girls against leaving their mothers' homes.\"<ref name=\"expr\">{{cite web|title='Tis the season for prostitution?|url=http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/_Tis_the_season_for_prostitution_-116547743.html|website=The Trinidad Express|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=19 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Report of West India Royal Commission (Moyne Report)]] (1960) concluded: \"Commercialised prostitution is not common as a profession in the West Indies. The high percentage of promiscuity in the Colonies puts prostitution into the category of a luxury profession. When this profession is followed, it is usually for economic reasons and because the wages earned by the woman in her other occupation are often too low to obtain the necessities of life for her.\"<ref name=\"expr\" />\n\n===World War 2===\nProstitution was a boom industry in the 1940s after the allied troops, especially American, were stationed on the islands during [[WW2]],<ref name=\"donald\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=O6lYKkEakd8C&pg=PA64&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago&f=false|title=Trinidad and Tobago: Democracy and Development in the Caribbean|first=Scott B.|last=MacDonald|date=1 January 1986|publisher=ABC-CLIO|accessdate=11 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780275920043}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women in wartime|url=http://www.trinidadexpress.com/commentaries/Women-in-wartime-232759751.html|website=The Trinidad Express|first=Bridget| last=Brereton |date=20 November 2013|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"essay\">{{cite web|title=Trinidad And Tobago By World War II History Essay|url=https://www.ukessays.com/essays/history/trinidad-and-tobago-by-world-war-ii-history-essay.php|website=UK Essays|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=23 March 2015}}</ref> especially around Port of Spain [[Arima]].<ref name=\"brereton\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uNrUU360mzsC&pg=PA90&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago&f=false|title=An Introduction to the History of Trinidad and Tobago|first=Bridget|last=Brereton|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Heinemann|accessdate=11 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780435984748}}</ref> In addition to the 100,000 troops,<ref name=\"friend\" /> the construction workers building the new American bases at [[Chaguaramas, Trinidad|Chaguaramas]] and [[Waller Field]]<ref name=\"donald\" /> added to the demand for prostitution.<ref name=\"brereton\" />\n\nThe spread of STIs was a problem in this era. The Governor of Trinidad and Tobago considered licencing the brothels in the country to ensure proper testing of the women, but this was never brought into force.<ref name=\"friend\">{{cite web|last1=McCollin|first1=Debbie|title=Friend or foe? Venereal diseases and the American presence in Trinidad and Tobago during World WarII |url=http://uwispace.sta.uwi.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/2139/11063/Article%203%20-%20VDS.pdf?sequence=1|publisher=The University of the West Indies|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=April 2010}}</ref> American Lt. Col. Fox recalled that when he visited in 1941, he was assured that every taxi driver could take him to a house of pleasure with any race of woman he desired.<ref name=\"friend\" />\n\n===Post WW2===\nAfter the closure of the US Air base at Waller Field in 1949, the demand for prostitution dropped.<ref name=\"essay\" />\n\nSociologist Lloyd Braithwaite noted in his 1953 survey Social Stratification in Trinidad wrote: \"In the lower-class sections of the town many well-known prostitutes abide, even though technically some have no fixed place of abode...the straitened and precarious economic circumstances that face working-class girls, particularly in the towns, must constantly make prostitution a temptation to them.\"<ref name=\"expr\" />\n\nThe demand for prostitutes further dropped when the US Naval base at Chaguaramas was scaled back in 1956 and finally closed in 1963.<ref name=\"essay\" /><ref>[http://www.chagdev.com/Pages/Chag-HistoryChaguaramas.htm Chaguaramas History at the Chaguaramas Development Authority] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820034747/http://www.chagdev.com/Pages/Chag-HistoryChaguaramas.htm |date=August 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Corruption==\nThe [[United States Department of State]] reports that prostitution is historically dependent on police corruption.<ref name=\"state16\">{{cite web|title=Trinidad and Tobago 2016 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2016/258880.htm|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref> There is also corruption of immigration officials<ref name=\"state16\" /> and police in regard to human trafficking.<ref name=\"newsday1\" /><ref name=\"state17\" /> Police provide protection for brothels. Some moonlight at the brothels and provide tip-offs of raids.<ref name=\"newsday1\" /> Part of their payment can be sex with the prostitutes.<ref name=\"newsday1\" />\n\nIn 2013, PC Valentine Eastman, a police officer for 23 years, was charged with 13<ref name=\"ttguard\">{{cite web|last1=Wilson|first1=Sascha|title=Cop to stand trial on 13 charges of human trafficking|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/2016-03-14/cop-stand-trial-13-charges-human-trafficking|website=The Trinidad Guardian Newspaper|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> human trafficking charges around 3 Colombian women trafficked to a brothel in [[Marabella]].<ref name=\"newsday1\" /> He was the first person in the [[British West Indies|British Caribbean]] to be charged with Human trafficking.<ref name=\"newsday1\" /> In 2016 he was committed to High Court for trial.<ref name=\"ttguard\" />\n\n==Sex tourism==\nThe islands are increasingly becoming a destination for [[sex tourism]].<ref name=\"campbell\" /><ref name=\"pope\" /><ref name=\"ipsnews\">{{cite web|last1=Gibbings|first1=Wesley|title=The High Cost of Sex Tourism|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/1997/03/trinidad-and-tobago-health-the-high-cost-of-sex-tourism/|website=IPS News|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=24 March 1997}}</ref> This tourism is blamed for the rise in HIV on the island.<ref name=\"pope\" /><ref name=\"ipsnews\" /> The Trinidadian Minister of Tourism observed that the rise in HIV/AIDs on the islands was becoming severe and out of control because of sex tourism and the beach-bum phenomenon.<ref name=\"daye\">{{cite book|last1=Daye|first1=Marcella|last2=Chambers|first2=Donna|last3=Roberts|first3=Sherma|title=New perspectives in Caribbean tourism|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0415897860|edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n\n===Female sex tourism===\nTobago is known as a destination for [[female sex tourism]].<ref name=\"guard\" /> European and American women come to the island seeking local men.<ref name=\"pope\" /> There is an organised tourist trade for the sex tourism; sometimes a local male is included in the price.<ref name=\"pope\" />\n\nIn 2016, Shadae Lamar Smith directed the short film ''The Resort'' based on sex tourism in Tobago. It was featured on [[Issa Rae]]'s [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fox|first1=Lauren R.D.|title=Issa Rae's #ShortFilmSundays Presents \"The Resort,\" An Expos\u00e9 On Sex Tourism|url=http://madamenoire.com/625550/sex-tourism/|website=Madame Noir|accessdate=23 December 2017|date=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Trinidad and Tobago}}\n[[Trinidad and Tobago]] is a destination, transit, and source country for adults and children subjected to sex trafficking. Women and girls from the [[Dominican Republic]], [[Guyana]], Venezuela, and Colombia are subjected to sex trafficking in brothels and clubs, often lured by offers of legitimate employment, with young women from Venezuela especially vulnerable. NGOs have previously heard reports about the availability of [[child sex trafficking]] victims advertised through classified ads and children are subjected to sex trafficking for commercial sex by Trinbagonians and foreign sex tourists. International criminal organisations are increasingly involved in trafficking. Police corruption has in the past been associated with facilitating prostitution and sex trafficking.<ref name=\"state17\">{{cite web|title=Trinidad and Tobago 2017 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271301.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703181538/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271301.htm|url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2017|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=3 January 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nMost of the victims of sex trafficking are brought into the country by boat, landing on southern peninsula of Trinidad in [[Icacos Point|Icacos]], [[Cedros, Trinidad and Tobago|Cedros]] and other neighbouring fishing villages.<ref name=\"newsday1\" />\n\nThe [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] ranks Trinidad and Tobago as a [[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 2]] country.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5ZLhRISXHIw The Resort] - Short film on [[YouTube]] about sex tourism.\n\n{{North America in topic|Prostitution in}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution in Trinidad and Tobago| ]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago society]]\n", "text_old": "'''Prostitution in Trinidad and Tobago''' is legal but related activities such as brothel keeping, soliciting and pimping are illegal.<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=3 January 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"soa86\">{{cite web|url=http://rgd.legalaffairs.gov.tt/laws2/alphabetical_list/lawspdfs/11.28.pdf |title=Laws of Trinidad and Tobago : Sexual Offences Act : Chapter 11:28 : Act 27 of 1986 |date=31 December 2015 |website=Rgd.legalaffairs.gov.tt |accessdate=2017-01-11}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Trinidad]], [[Port of Spain]] is the main place of sex work,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caribbean360.com/news/trinidad_tobago_news/women-trafficked-for-prostitution-and-forced-marriage-in-trinidad|title=Women trafficked for prostitution and forced marriage in Trinidad - Caribbean360|date=24 January 2014|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ips\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/1996/02/trinidad-and-tobago-child-prostitution-is-a-thriving-business/|title=Trinidad and Tobago: Child Prostitution Is A Thriving Business - Inter Press Service|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> including [[street prostitution]] on Roberts and Murray Streets.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=John|title=What about street prostitutes, Louis?|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/letters/2011/02/14/what-about-street-prostitutes-louis|website=The Trinidad Guardian Newspaper|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=15 February 2011}}</ref> New [[brothels]] continue to open across the country, particularly in the south where they are incorporated into small bars and rum shops and are difficult to detect, and in central, where they operate out of a normal-looking flats in a neighbourhood.<ref name=\"state16\" /> Many of the sex workers come from [[Colombia]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Cuba]]. Some regularly commute between their home nation and Trinidad.<ref name=\"pope\">{{cite book|last1=Pope|first1=Cynthia|last2=White|first2=Ren\u00e9e T.|last3=Malow|first3=Robert|title=HIV/AIDS : global frontiers in prevention/intervention|date=2009|publisher=Routledge|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0415953832}}</ref>\n\nProstitution in less common in [[Tobago]], some prostitutes from Trinidad move to Tobago for the tourist season.<ref name=\"guard\" /><ref name=\"ipsnews\" />\n\nThe country is a [[sex tourism]] destination.<ref name=\"campbell\">{{cite book|last1=Niblett|first1=Michael|last2=Campbell|first2=Chris |title=The Caribbean: Aesthetics, World-Ecology, Politics (Postcolonialism Across the Disciplines)|date=31 May 2016|publisher=Liverpool University Press|isbn=978-1781382950}}</ref> \nTobago is also known as a destination for [[female sex tourism]].<ref name=\"guard\">{{cite web|last1=Fido|first1=Austin|title=The shady side of paradise|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2015-09-20/shady-side-paradise|website=Trinidad & Tobago Guardian|accessdate=23 December 2017|date=20 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Sex trafficking]] is a problem in the country,<ref name=\"sextour\">{{cite web|title=16 Caribbean Nations Where Sex Trafficking Remains A Problem {{!}} News Americas Now:Caribbean and Latin America Daily News|url=http://www.newsamericasnow.com/16-caribbean-nations-where-sex-trafficking-remains-a-problem/|website=News Americas Now|accessdate=30 December 2017|date=30 June 2016}}</ref> as is [[child prostitution]].<ref name=\"ips\" />\n\n==Legislation==\nBeing a former [[British Empire|British colony]], much of the prostitution law mirrors that of the [[UK]]:\n\n* The 1921 Summary Offences Act<ref name=\"sum21\">{{cite web|title=Laws of Trinidad and Tobago: Summary Offences Act Chapter 11:02|url=http://rgd.legalaffairs.gov.tt/laws2/alphabetical_list/lawspdfs/11.02.pdf|publisher=Government of Trinidad and Tobago|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=1921}}</ref> \n** Section 46: any woman loitering about and soliciting passers-by for the purpose of prostitution, on the second occasion, may be deemed a rogue and vagabond, and shall be liable to imprisonment for two months\n* The 1986 Sexual Offences Act<ref name=\"soa86\" />\n**Section 17: Any person who procures another for prostitution; or procures another to become an inmate of or to frequent a brothel; is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for fifteen years\n** Section 19: A person who detains another against that other\u2019s will in any brothel, is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for ten years.\n** Section 22: A person who keeps or manages or acts or assists in the management of a brothel; or being the tenant, lessee, occupier or person in charge of any premises, knowingly permits the premises or any part thereof to be used as a brothel or for the purposes of prostitution; is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for five years.\n** Section 23. (1) A person who\u2014\n***(a) knowingly lives wholly or in part on the earnings of prostitution; or\n***(b) in any place solicits for immoral purposes,\n::is guilty of an offence and is liable on conviction to imprisonment for five years\n* Human trafficking is dealt with by the Trafficking In Persons Act 2011.<ref name=\"newsday1\">{{cite web|last1=Connelly|first1=Corey|title=100 Arrivals Weekly|url=http://archives.newsday.co.tt/2015/07/12/100-arrivals-weekly/|website=Trinidad and Tobago Newsday|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=12 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Colonial period===\nDuring the slave period, slaves could sometimes be hired as prostitutes.<ref name=\"plant\">{{cite book|last1=Trotman|first1=David Vincent|title=Crime in Trinidad : conflict and control in a plantation society, 1838-1900|url=https://archive.org/details/crimeintrinidadc0000trot|url-access=registration|date=1986|publisher=University of Tennessee Press|location=Knoxville, TN|isbn=978-0870494918|edition=1st}}</ref> After the abolition of slavery (1838), many [[mulatto]] women became prostitutes or brothel madams, often moving from rural areas to towns such as Port of Spain.<ref name=\"plant\" />\n\nIn an effort to control the spread of [[sexually transmitted infections|STIs]] the Contagious Diseases Ordinance was introduced in 1869.<ref name=\"plant\" /> This was based in the similar [[Contagious Diseases Acts|British Act of 1864]]. Prostitutes were required to be registered and have regular examinations for STIs.<ref name=\"plant\" /> The ordinance was suspended in 1872 and reintroduced in 1875.<ref name=\"plant\" /> The register showed a significant number of prostitutes to be working in Port of Spain and [[San Fernando, Trinidad and Tobago|San Fernando]].<ref name=\"colonial\" /> Unscrupulous policemen took advantage of the ordinance to demand sexual favours. In  Port of Spain, a Sergeant Holder was given unlimited power to enforce the ordinance. He abused his position and, following an investigation brought about by a complaint, was dismissed from the force.<ref name=\"plant\" /> The ordinance was abolished in 1887.<ref name=\"plant\" />\n\nThe sugar slump of the 1880s<ref name=\"colonial\" /> brought many more women to the towns, turning to prostitution to try and make a living.<ref name=\"plant\" /> At this time, Port of Spain was reported to have more prostitutes than any other town in the [[West Indies]].<ref name=\"colonial\">{{cite book|last1=Brereton|first1=Bridget|title=Race relations in colonial Trinidad, 1870-1900|date=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0521523134|edition=Paperback}}</ref> Most of the taverns in the town were brothels, and the best brothel was reputed to be the \"British Coffee House\", run by a Mrs Peery.<ref name=\"plant\" /> Many of the prostitutes were underage and lived on the streets.<ref name=\"colonial\" />\n\n===1930's===\nDuring the [[Great Depression]] in the 1930s, more women turned to prostitution. In his book, ''Calypso and Society'', [[Gordon Rohlehr]] noted: \"Some singers, indeed, presented the vocation of prostitution as the only alternative to that of housewifery, and warned young girls against leaving their mothers' homes.\"<ref name=\"expr\">{{cite web|title='Tis the season for prostitution?|url=http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/_Tis_the_season_for_prostitution_-116547743.html|website=The Trinidad Express|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=19 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Report of West India Royal Commission (Moyne Report)]] (1960) concluded: \"Commercialised prostitution is not common as a profession in the West Indies. The high percentage of promiscuity in the Colonies puts prostitution into the category of a luxury profession. When this profession is followed, it is usually for economic reasons and because the wages earned by the woman in her other occupation are often too low to obtain the necessities of life for her.\"<ref name=\"expr\" />\n\n===World War 2===\nProstitution was a boom industry in the 1940s after the allied troops, especially American, were stationed on the islands during [[WW2]],<ref name=\"donald\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=O6lYKkEakd8C&pg=PA64&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago&f=false|title=Trinidad and Tobago: Democracy and Development in the Caribbean|first=Scott B.|last=MacDonald|date=1 January 1986|publisher=ABC-CLIO|accessdate=11 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780275920043}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women in wartime|url=http://www.trinidadexpress.com/commentaries/Women-in-wartime-232759751.html|website=The Trinidad Express|first=Bridget| last=Brereton |date=20 November 2013|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"essay\">{{cite web|title=Trinidad And Tobago By World War II History Essay|url=https://www.ukessays.com/essays/history/trinidad-and-tobago-by-world-war-ii-history-essay.php|website=UK Essays|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=23 March 2015}}</ref> especially around Port of Spain [[Arima]].<ref name=\"brereton\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uNrUU360mzsC&pg=PA90&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago&f=false|title=An Introduction to the History of Trinidad and Tobago|first=Bridget|last=Brereton|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Heinemann|accessdate=11 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780435984748}}</ref> In addition to the 100,000 troops,<ref name=\"friend\" /> the construction workers building the new American bases at [[Chaguaramas, Trinidad|Chaguaramas]] and [[Waller Field]]<ref name=\"donald\" /> added to the demand for prostitution.<ref name=\"brereton\" />\n\nThe spread of STIs was a problem in this era. The Governor of Trinidad and Tobago considered licencing the brothels in the country to ensure proper testing of the women, but this was never brought into force.<ref name=\"friend\">{{cite web|last1=McCollin|first1=Debbie|title=Friend or foe? Venereal diseases and the American presence in Trinidad and Tobago during World WarII |url=http://uwispace.sta.uwi.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/2139/11063/Article%203%20-%20VDS.pdf?sequence=1|publisher=The University of the West Indies|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=April 2010}}</ref> American Lt. Col. Fox recalled that when he visited in 1941, he was assured that every taxi driver could take him to a house of pleasure with any race of woman he desired.<ref name=\"friend\" />\n\n===Post WW2===\nAfter the closure of the US Air base at Waller Field in 1949, the demand for prostitution dropped.<ref name=\"essay\" />\n\nSociologist Lloyd Braithwaite noted in his 1953 survey Social Stratification in Trinidad wrote: \"In the lower-class sections of the town many well-known prostitutes abide, even though technically some have no fixed place of abode...the straitened and precarious economic circumstances that face working-class girls, particularly in the towns, must constantly make prostitution a temptation to them.\"<ref name=\"expr\" />\n\nThe demand for prostitutes further dropped when the US Naval base at Chaguaramas was scaled back in 1956 and finally closed in 1963.<ref name=\"essay\" /><ref>[http://www.chagdev.com/Pages/Chag-HistoryChaguaramas.htm Chaguaramas History at the Chaguaramas Development Authority] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820034747/http://www.chagdev.com/Pages/Chag-HistoryChaguaramas.htm |date=August 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Corruption==\nThe [[United States Department of State]] reports that prostitution is historically dependent on police corruption.<ref name=\"state16\">{{cite web|title=Trinidad and Tobago 2016 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2016/258880.htm|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref> There is also corruption of immigration officials<ref name=\"state16\" /> and police in regard to human trafficking.<ref name=\"newsday1\" /><ref name=\"state17\" /> Police provide protection for brothels. Some moonlight at the brothels and provide tip-offs of raids.<ref name=\"newsday1\" /> Part of their payment can be sex with the prostitutes.<ref name=\"newsday1\" />\n\nIn 2013, PC Valentine Eastman, a police officer for 23 years, was charged with 13<ref name=\"ttguard\">{{cite web|last1=Wilson|first1=Sascha|title=Cop to stand trial on 13 charges of human trafficking|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/2016-03-14/cop-stand-trial-13-charges-human-trafficking|website=The Trinidad Guardian Newspaper|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> human trafficking charges around 3 Colombian women trafficked to a brothel in [[Marabella]].<ref name=\"newsday1\" /> He was the first person in the [[British West Indies|British Caribbean]] to be charged with Human trafficking.<ref name=\"newsday1\" /> In 2016 he was committed to High Court for trial.<ref name=\"ttguard\" />\n\n==Sex tourism==\nThe islands are increasingly becoming a destination for [[sex tourism]].<ref name=\"campbell\" /><ref name=\"pope\" /><ref name=\"ipsnews\">{{cite web|last1=Gibbings|first1=Wesley|title=The High Cost of Sex Tourism|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/1997/03/trinidad-and-tobago-health-the-high-cost-of-sex-tourism/|website=IPS News|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=24 March 1997}}</ref> This tourism is blamed for the rise in HIV on the island.<ref name=\"pope\" /><ref name=\"ipsnews\" /> The Trinidadian Minister of Tourism observed that the rise in HIV/AIDs on the islands was becoming severe and out of control because of sex tourism and the beach-bum phenomenon.<ref name=\"daye\">{{cite book|last1=Daye|first1=Marcella|last2=Chambers|first2=Donna|last3=Roberts|first3=Sherma|title=New perspectives in Caribbean tourism|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0415897860|edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n\n===Female sex tourism===\nTobago is known as a destination for [[female sex tourism]].<ref name=\"guard\" /> European and American women come to the island seeking local men.<ref name=\"pope\" /> There is an organised tourist trade for the sex tourism; sometimes a local male is included in the price.<ref name=\"pope\" />\n\nIn 2016, Shadae Lamar Smith directed the short film ''The Resort'' based on sex tourism in Tobago. It was featured on [[Issa Rae]]'s [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fox|first1=Lauren R.D.|title=Issa Rae's #ShortFilmSundays Presents \"The Resort,\" An Expos\u00e9 On Sex Tourism|url=http://madamenoire.com/625550/sex-tourism/|website=Madame Noir|accessdate=23 December 2017|date=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Trinidad and Tobago}}\n[[Trinidad and Tobago]] is a destination, transit, and source country for adults and children subjected to sex trafficking. Women and girls from the [[Dominican Republic]], [[Guyana]], Venezuela, and Colombia are subjected to sex trafficking in brothels and clubs, often lured by offers of legitimate employment, with young women from Venezuela especially vulnerable. NGOs have previously heard reports about the availability of [[child sex trafficking]] victims advertised through classified ads and children are subjected to sex trafficking for commercial sex by Trinbagonians and foreign sex tourists. International criminal organisations are increasingly involved in trafficking. Police corruption has in the past been associated with facilitating prostitution and sex trafficking.<ref name=\"state17\">{{cite web|title=Trinidad and Tobago 2017 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271301.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703181538/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271301.htm|url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2017|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=3 January 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nMost of the victims of sex trafficking are brought into the country by boat, landing on southern peninsula of Trinidad in [[Icacos Point|Icacos]], [[Cedros, Trinidad and Tobago|Cedros]] and other neighbouring fishing villages.<ref name=\"newsday1\" />\n\nThe [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] ranks Trinidad and Tobago as a [[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 2]] country.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5ZLhRISXHIw The Resort] - Short film on [[YouTube]] about sex tourism.\n\n{{North America in topic|Prostitution in}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution in Trinidad and Tobago| ]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago society]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegislation:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prostitution_in_Trinidad_and_Tobago"}
{"title_page": "Naben Ruthnum", "text_new": "'''Naben Ruthnum''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] writer, who has published work under both his own name and the pen name '''Nathan Ripley'''.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/authors/how-nathan-ripley-subverts-genre-conventions-in-his-debut-thriller-find-you-in-the-dark/ \"How Nathan Ripley subverts genre conventions in his debut thriller, Find You in the Dark\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', January 2018.</ref>\n\nHe won the [[Journey Prize]] in 2013 for his short story \"Cinema Rex\",<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/awards/2013/11/21/mcadam-moore-both-winners-at-writers-trust-awards/ \"McAdam, Moore both among winners at Writers\u2019 Trust awards\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', November 21, 2013.</ref> and has since published the books ''Curry: Reading, Eating and Race'' (2017), a non-fiction essay collection about immigrant cultural identity in food and literature,<ref>[https://nowtoronto.com/art-and-books/books/jan-wong-naben-ruthnum-food-and-family/ \"Toronto authors explore food and family in two wildly different books\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', September 13, 2017.</ref> and ''Find You in the Dark'', a literary thriller novel.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/book-reviews/review-nathan-ripleys-cracking-good-debut-thriller-find-you-in-the-dark/article38318925/ \"Review: Nathan Ripley\u2019s cracking good debut thriller Find You in the Dark\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', March 22, 2018.</ref>\n\nOriginally from [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]], Ruthnum is of [[Mauritius|Mauritian]] descent.<ref name=asianheritage>[https://library.ryerson.ca/asianheritage/authors/naben-ruthnum/ \"Naben Ruthnum\"]. ''Asian Heritage in Canada''.</ref> He has a master's degree from [[McGill University]], where he wrote his thesis on the role of [[Oscar Wilde]] in the development of the [[ghost story]] in British literature.<ref name=asianheritage/>\n\nOutside of his literary work, Ruthnum is also a former musician, most notable as the founding guitarist for [[Bend Sinister (band)|Bend Sinister]], a [[Vancouver]]-based [[progressive rock]] band.<ref>http://www.sfu.ca/archive-sfunews/print/Stories/sfunews101608012.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruthnum, Naben}}\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian short story writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian writers of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Mauritian descent]]\n[[Category:Writers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:People from Kelowna]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian thriller writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male essayists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n\n\n{{Canada-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Naben Ruthnum''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] writer, who has published work under both his own name and the pen name '''Nathan Ripley'''.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/authors/how-nathan-ripley-subverts-genre-conventions-in-his-debut-thriller-find-you-in-the-dark/ \"How Nathan Ripley subverts genre conventions in his debut thriller, Find You in the Dark\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', January 2018.</ref>\n\nHe won the [[Journey Prize]] in 2013 for his short story \"Cinema Rex\",<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/awards/2013/11/21/mcadam-moore-both-winners-at-writers-trust-awards/ \"McAdam, Moore both among winners at Writers\u2019 Trust awards\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', November 21, 2013.</ref> and has since published the books ''Curry: Reading, Eating and Race'' (2017), a non-fiction essay collection about immigrant cultural identity in food and literature,<ref>[https://nowtoronto.com/art-and-books/books/jan-wong-naben-ruthnum-food-and-family/ \"Toronto authors explore food and family in two wildly different books\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', September 13, 2017.</ref> and ''Find You in the Dark'', a literary thriller novel.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/book-reviews/review-nathan-ripleys-cracking-good-debut-thriller-find-you-in-the-dark/article38318925/ \"Review: Nathan Ripley\u2019s cracking good debut thriller Find You in the Dark\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', March 22, 2018.</ref>\n\nOriginally from [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]], Ruthnum is of [[Mauritius|Mauritian]] descent.<ref name=asianheritage>[https://library.ryerson.ca/asianheritage/authors/naben-ruthnum/ \"Naben Ruthnum\"]. ''Asian Heritage in Canada''.</ref> He has a master's degree from [[McGill University]], where he wrote his thesis on the role of [[Oscar Wilde]] in the development of the [[ghost story]] in British literature.<ref name=asianheritage/>\n\nOutside of his literary work, Ruthnum is also a former musician, most notable as the founding guitarist for [[Bend Sinister (band)|Bend Sinister]], a [[Vancouver]]-based [[progressive rock]] band. <ref>http://www.sfu.ca/archive-sfunews/print/Stories/sfunews101608012.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruthnum, Naben}}\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian short story writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian essayists]]\n[[Category:Canadian writers of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Mauritian descent]]\n[[Category:Writers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:People from Kelowna]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian thriller writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n\n\n{{Canada-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment"